				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Wed Nov 10, 2004 6:47 pm<br /><b>Posts:</b> 1670
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">n6 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">so the update should be called 4 times per frame for NTSC and 5 times if the other mode is selected in $4017.</div><br /><br /><em>Roughly</em> 4 times per frame -- yes.  As far as I can tell the sequencer is driven by the CPU clock, so it will <em>not</em> work to an even number of times per frame.  4 Sequencer steps is either a little bit shorter or a little bit longer (I forget which) than the length of one PPU frame.<br /><br />In the 5-step mode... there are more steps before the sequence loops, however the steps are NOT any closer together -- so 5-step mode will slow the rate at which length/etc are clocked.  In this case... the full 5-step sequence is <em>considerably longer</em> than one PPU frame.<br /><br />So basically what I'm getting at -- is don't do ANYTHING on a per-frame basis.  A frame has nothing to do with APU operations.  The channels and sequencer are all driven by the CPU clock rate -- not the PPU framerate.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">But what is meant by reset, when writing to $4017? just that the step is set to 0</div><br /><br />Yeah, it sets the step to step 0, and it also changes the number of cycles until the next step.  For details on how this works, pick up blargg's APU test ROMs.  The documentation included covers APU sequencer timing.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">How do I know if its Length or Linear that I should use?</div><br /><br />When length is clocked (every other step in the 4-step sequence), you clock the lenght.  When Linear is clocked (every step in the sequence 4-step sequence) you clock the linear.<br /><br />Both counters operate independently of each other, and both can silence the channel... so if EITHER counter is 0, the channel is silent.  In order for the Tri to be playing anything, both linear and length counters must be nonzero.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Okey but I just count them down and when one of them reach zero I stop the channel</div><br /><br />Yes.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">and reset the other to zero?</div>
<br />
<br />No.
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />If I were you -- I wouldn't worry about the sequencer and subsystems yet -- and I'd just get sound playing.  Like make the squares just output tones without doing the decay/sweep/length units.  You can always add the sequencer later, and perhaps you might have a better idea of what to do after working with the main channel.
<br />
<br />The APU is a pretty big area, and trying to get in all in your first bite may be a bit rough.</div>

